-elisabeth-koegler-an-seine-majestaet-koenig-tupou-vi-des-koenigreichs-tonga-und-treffen-mit-dem-amtierenden-premierminister-hon-samiu-vaipulu |access-date=1 January 2025}}</ref>\n|-\n|83\n|{{Flag|Qatar}}\n|{{dts|16 February 2024}}\n|-\n|84\n|{{Flag|Nicaragua}}\n|{{Dts|28 February 2024}}\n|-\n|85\n|{{Flag|Dominican Republic}}\n|{{Dts|29 February 2024}}\n|-\n|86\n|{{Flag|Nepal}}\n|{{DTS|1 March 2024}}\n|-\n|87\n|{{Flag|Oman}}\n|{{Dts|14 March 2024}}\n|-\n|88\n|{{Flag|Uruguay}}\n|{{Dts|14 March 2024}}\n|-\n|89\n|{{Flag|Uganda}}\n|{{Dts|15 April 2024}}<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 April 2024 |title=H.E Dorothy Samali Hyuha presents credentials to his Majesty the King of Tonga, at the royal palace of the Kingdom of Tonga, 15th April 2024 |url=https://canberra.mofa.go.ug/media/he-dorothy-samali-hyuha-presents-credentials-his-majesty-king-tonga-royal-palace-kingdom-tonga |access-date=20 June 2024 |website=The High Commission of the Republic of Uganda Canbera - Australia}}</ref>\n|-\n|—\n|{{Flag|Kosovo}}\n|{{Date table sorting|17 April 2024}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 April 2024 |title=Facebook post |url=https://www.facebook.com/KosovoinAustralia/posts/pfbid0kQTBduYY1m6KNbvBZgrD9gutqFrCUV28QhVVRGTCZcahJ7P1paUnbn5vzUUrj7fMl |access-date=19 June 2024}}</ref>\n|-\n|90\n|{{Flag|Lithuania}}\n|{{Dts|23 September 2024}}\n|-\n|91\n|{{Flag|Dominica}}\n|{{Dts|25 October 2024}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=25 October 2024 |title=Tonga and Dominica establish diplomatic relations |url=https://talanoaotonga.to/tonga-and-dominica-establish-diplomatic-relations/ |access-date=25 October 2024}}</ref>\n|-\n|92\n|{{Flag|San Marino}}\n|{{Dts|25 February 2025}}<ref>{{Cite web |date=3 March 2025 |title=Tonga establishes diplomatic ties with San Marino |url=https://matangitonga.to/2025/03/03/tonga-establishes-diplomatic-ties-san-marino |access-date=3 March 2025 |website=matangitonga.to}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Regional relations==\n\nTonga maintains strong regional ties in the Pacific. It is a full member of the [[Pacific Islands Forum]], the [[South Pacific Applied Geoscience Commission]], the [[South Pacific Tourism Organisation]], the [[Pacific Regional Environment Programme]] and the [[Secretariat of the Pacific Community]].  Tonga endorsed the [[Treaty of Rarotonga]] (the South Pacific Nuclear Free Zone Treaty) in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forumsec.org/resources/uploads/attachments/documents/SPNFZ%20Status%20Report.pdf |title=SOUTH PACIFIC NUCLEAR FREE ZONE TREATY  |publisher=Pacific Islands Forum |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084144/http://www.forumsec.org/resources/uploads/attachments/documents/SPNFZ%20Status%20Report.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTonga is, however, notably not one of the eight signatories of the [[Nauru Agreement Concerning Cooperation in the Management of Fisheries of Common Interest]] which collectively controls 25–30% of the world's tuna supply and approximately 60% of the western and central Pacific tuna supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://klima-tuvalu.no/2011/04/13/pacific-islands-fighting-for-their-tuna/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819123129/http://klima-tuvalu.no/2011/04/13/pacific-islands-fighting-for-their-tuna/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 August 2011 |title=Pacific islands fighting for their tuna &#124; Klima-Tuvalu |date=19 August 2011 |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince November 2011, Tonga has been one of the eight founding members of [[Polynesian Leaders Group]], a regional grouping intended to cooperate on a variety of issues including culture and language, education, responses to climate change, and trade and investment.<ref name=\"scoop\">{{cite news|last1=Andrews|first1=John|title=NZ may be invited to join proposed 'Polynesian Triangle' ginger group|url=http://pacific.scoop.co.nz/2011/09/nz-may-be-invited-to-join-proposed-polynesian-triangle-ginger-group/|access-date=20 November 2011|agency=Pacific Scoop News|publisher=Scoop News|date=19 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"RNZI\">{{cite news|title=New Polynesian Leaders Group formed in Samoa|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/200981/new-polynesian-leaders-group-formed-in-samoa|access-date=20 November 2011|agency=Radio New Zealand|date=19 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Savali\">{{cite news |title=American Samoa joins Polynesian Leaders Group, MOU signed |url=https://www.samoanews.com/american-samoa-joins-poly-leaders-group-mou-signed |access-date=30 July 2020 |work=Samoa News |agency=Savalii |date=20 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Extra-regional relations==\n\nTonga was admitted to full membership of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] in 1970, upon regaining its independence from British protection.\n\nSince it has always had its own monarch, its position in the Commonwealth was rather unusual.\n\nTonga is an independent native [[Commonwealth monarchy]] like [[Brunei]], [[Lesotho]], [[Malaysia]], and [[Swaziland]].\n \nTonga was admitted to the United Nations in 1999.\n\nAdditionally outside the region, Tonga is a member or participant of the [[ACP (Lomé Convention)|ACP]], [[Asian Development Bank]], [[Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific]] (ESCAP), the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO), the [[Group of 77|G-77]], the [[International Bank for Reconstruction and Development]], the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]], the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement]], the [[International Development Association]], the [[International Finance Corporation]], [[International Hydrographic Organization]], the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]], the [[International Maritime Organization]], [[Interpol (organization)|Interpol]], the [[International Olympic Committee]], the [[International Telecommunication Union|ITU]], the [[Non-Aligned Movement|NAM]], the [[Universal Postal Union|UPU]], the [[World Meteorological Organization]] and the [[World Trade Organization]].\n\n==Bilateral relations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Australia}}||4 June 1970||See [[Australia–Tonga relations]]\n\n* Australia has a high commission in [[Nukuʻalofa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tonga.embassy.gov.au |title=Australian High Commission in Tonga |publisher=Tonga.embassy.gov.au |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Tonga has a high commission in [[Canberra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tongahighcom.com.au |title=Tongan High Commission in Australia |publisher=Tongahighcom.com.au |date=9 September 2015 |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Brazil}}||21 December 2011||\n\n* Brazil is accredited to Tonga from its embassy in Wellington, New Zealand.\n* Tonga does not have an accreditation to Brazil.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Canada}}||11 June 1971||\n\n* Canada is accredited to Tonga from its High Commission in Wellington, New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/new_zealand-nouvelle_zelande/index.aspx?lang=eng |title=Canadian High Commission in New Zealand |publisher=Canadainternational.gc.ca |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Tonga is accredited to Canada from its Permanent Mission to the United Nations in New York City.<ref name=UN>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.int/tonga/ |title=Tongan Permanent Mission to the United Nations |publisher=United Nations |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|China}}||2 November 1998||See [[China–Tonga relations]]\n\nThe Kingdom of Tonga and the People's Republic of China (PRC) established official diplomatic relations in 1998. The two countries maintain cordial diplomatic, economic and military relations. \n* China has an embassy in Nukuʻalofa.\n* Tonga has an embassy in Beijing.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Fiji}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Fiji–Tonga relations]]\n\nThese neighbouring countries in the South Pacific have a history of bilateral relations going back several centuries.\n\nFiji's Prime Minister [[Frank Bainimarama|Voreqe Bainimarama]] received \"cheers and thunderous applause\" from the Tongan public when he attended a [[Pacific Islands Forum]] meeting in Tonga in October 2007; the crowd's \"enthusiastic reception\" of Fiji's leader was likened to \"that accorded to a rock star\".<ref>[http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=72451 \"Voreqe no 'leper'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920115658/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=72451 |date=20 September 2008 }}, Maria Burese, ''Fiji Times'', 17 October 2007.</ref> [[Radio Australia]] noted that he had been \"the star of this year's meeting, for the people of Tonga\",<ref>[http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/programguide/stories/200710/s2063340.htm \"TONGA: Questions over Fiji election commitment\"], ABC Radio Australia, 18 October 2007.</ref> while [[TVNZ]] reported that he had been \"given a hero's welcome\".<ref name=\"tvnz\">{{cite web |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/425825/1404976 |title=Clark snubbed, Bainimarama welcomed |date=16 October 2007 |work=[[Television New Zealand]] |access-date=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of inter-governmental relations, Tonga has generally avoided pressuring Fiji's \"interim government\" into holding democratic elections. However, Tongan Prime Minister Dr. [[Feleti Sevele]] has urged Bainimarama \"to produce a credible roadmap to the election according to the [[1997 Constitution of Fiji|Constitution]] and law of Fiji\".<ref>[http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=72501 \"Bainimarama vows army will abide by results of 2009 election\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018001933/http://fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=72501 |date=18 October 2007 }}, ''Fiji Times'', 17 October 2007.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Germany}}||1 May 1976||\n\n* Germany is accredited to Tonga from its embassy in Wellington, New Zealand and maintains an honorary consulate in Nukuʻalofa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wellington.diplo.de/nz-en/botschaft/honorarkonsuln?openAccordionId=item-1774768-5-panel |title=Honorary Consuls – Federal Foreign Office |publisher=Wellington.diplo.de |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Tonga is accredited to Germany from its high commission in London, United Kingdom.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Greece}}||<!--Date started-->1984||\n\n* Diplomatic relations were established in 1984.<ref name=\"mfa.gr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gr/en/blog/greece-bilateral-relations/tonga/ |title=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Greece |publisher=Mfa.gr |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Greece is accredited to Tonga from its embassy in Wellington, New Zealand.<ref name=\"mfa.gr\"/>\n* Tonga does not have an accreditation to Greece.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|India}}||23 December 1970||See [[India–Tonga relations]]\n\n* India is accredited to Tonga from its high commission in Suva, Fiji.\n* Tonga does not have an accreditation to India.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Japan}}||July 1970||\n\n* Japan has an embassy in Nukuʻalofa.\n* Tonga has an embassy in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tongaembassy.jp |title=Tonga Embassy in Japan |publisher=Tongaembassy.jp |date=31 January 2019 |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Latvia}}||28 October 2020||\n\n* Tonga and [[Latvia]] established diplomatic relations in 2020. On 28 October 2020, Tongan and Latvian Ambassadors to the United Nations signed a joint communiqué formalising the bilateral relations and expressed satisfaction over strengthening of ties between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfa.gov.lv/aktualitates/zinas/66873-latvija-izveido-diplomatiskas-attiecibas-ar-tongu |title=Latvia Establishes Diplomatic Relations with Tonga |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Latvia |date=29 October 2020 |access-date=29 October 2020}}</ref>\n* Both countries see opportunities for cooperation in tackling climate change, development cooperation, economics, and cooperation in various multilateral formats, especially in the light of the prospective Latvian non-permanent membership of the [[United Nations Security Council]] in 2026–2027.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfa.gov.lv/arpolitika/starptautiskas-organizacijas/latvija-apvienoto-naciju-organizacija/latvijas-kandidaturas |title=Latvia's Candidacies |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Latvia |date=17 September 2020 |access-date=29 October 2020}}</ref>\n* In October 2024, the Speaker of the Tongan Parliament [[Fatafehi Fakafanua]] expressed support for Latvia's nomination to join the [[United Nations Security Council]] in June 2025.<ref name=\"Latvian Parliament 24 Oct 2025\">{{cite web |title=Speaker of the Saeima Daiga Mieriņa welcomes the Speakers of the Parliaments of Albania, Croatia, Cyprus, Portugal, and Tonga, emphasising support for Ukraine |url=https://www.saeima.lv/en/news/saeima-news/34012-speaker-of-the-saeima-daiga-mierina-welcomes-the-speakers-of-the-parliaments-of-albania-croatia-cyprus-portugal-and-tonga-emphasising-support-for-ukraine |publisher=[[Saiema]] |access-date=6 May 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241212211707/https://www.saeima.lv/en/news/saeima-news/34012-speaker-of-the-saeima-daiga-mierina-welcomes-the-speakers-of-the-parliaments-of-albania-croatia-cyprus-portugal-and-tonga-emphasising-support-for-ukraine |archive-date=12 December 2024 |date=24 October 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mexico}}||6 September 2008||\n\n* Mexico is accredited to Tonga from its embassy in Wellington, New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://embamex.sre.gob.mx/nuevazelandia/ |title=Embassy of Mexico in New Zealand (in English and Spanish) |publisher=Embamex.sre.gob.mx |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Tonga is accredited to Mexico from its Permanent Mission to the United Nations in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.int/tonga/ |title=Permanent Mission of Tonga to the United Nations |publisher=United Nations |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|New Zealand}}||4 June 1970||See [[New Zealand–Tonga relations]]\n\n* New Zealand has a high commission in Nukuʻalofa.<ref>[https://www.mfat.govt.nz/en/countries-and-regions/pacific/tonga/new-zealand-high-commission/ High Commission of New Zealand in Nukuʻalofa]</ref>\n* Tonga has a consulate-general in [[Auckland]].<ref>[https://www.mfat.govt.nz/en/countries-and-regions/pacific/tonga/consulate-of-the-kingdom-of-tonga/ Consulate-General of Tonga in Auckland]</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Russia}}||14 October 1975||See [[Russia–Tonga relations]]\n\nThe Kingdom of Tonga and the [[Soviet Union]] established formal diplomatic relations in 1976.  Tonga was the first [[Pacific Island]] country to establish relations with the USSR.  The USSR was dissolved in 1991 and was succeeded by Russia as the successor state.\n\nOn 2 October 2005, Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation [[Sergey Lavrov]] and Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Kingdom of Tonga ST T. Tupou exchanged telegrams offering congratulations on the occasion of 30th anniversary of establishing diplomatic relations between the two nations. In his heads of foreign ministries of Russia and Tonga expressed confidence in further development of Russian-Tongan relations in the interests of the peoples of both countries and strengthen peace and security in the Asia-Pacific region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.ru/ns-rafr.nsf/89414576079db559432569d8002421fc/432569a400373407c325709000373b1b?OpenDocument |title=On the exchange of greeting telegrams between the Foreign Ministers of the Russian Federation and the Kingdom of Tonga on the occasion of 30 anniversary of establishment of diplomatic relations |publisher=Mid.ru |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Russia is accredited to Tonga from its embassy in Canberra, Australia.\n* Tonga does not have an accreditation to Russia.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Samoa}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Samoa–Tonga relations]]\n\nBoth nations are [[Pacific Islands]] countries and members of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and [[Pacific Islands Forum]].\n* Samoa is accredited to Tonga from its Ministry of Foreign Affairs in [[Apia]].\n* Tonga is accredited to Samoa from its Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Nukuʻalofa.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Korea}}||11 September 1970||\n\nThe Kingdom of Tonga and the Republic of Korea have established diplomatic relations on September 11, 1970.\n* The two countries have good diplomatic relations.  \n* The ROK's Investment in Tonga in 2019 was about 2.5 million $.<ref>https://www.mofa.go.kr/eng/nation/m_4902/view.do?seq=35 {{Bare URL inline|date=August 2024}}</ref> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Spain }}||16 November 1979||\n\n* Spain is accredited to Tonga from its embassy in Wellington, New Zealand.\n* Tonga does not have an accreditation to Spain\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|{{flag| Turkey}}||<!--Date started-->26 January 1976<ref name=\"auto11\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/relations-between-turkey-and-the-kingdom-of-tonga.en.mfa| title=Relations between Turkey and Tonga|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |access-date=6 October 2020}}</ref>||See [[Tonga–Turkey relations]]\n*Turkish ambassador in [[Wellington]] to New Zealand is also accredited to [[Tonga]].<ref name=\"auto11\"/>\n* Trade volume between the two countries was negligible in 2019.<ref name=\"auto11\"/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United Kingdom}} || 4 June 1970 || See [[Tonga–United Kingdom relations]]\nTonga established [[Foreign relations of the United Kingdom|diplomatic relations with the United Kingdom]] on 4 June 1970.<ref name=\"britain\" />\n*Tonga maintains a [[High Commission of Tonga, London|high commission]] in London.<ref>{{#invoke:cite|web|author=Diplomat Magazine|date=1 February 2016|url=https://diplomatmagazine.com/heads-of-mission/oceania/tonga/|title=Tonga|website=Diplomat Magazine|access-date=15 July 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250613100407/https://diplomatmagazine.com/heads-of-mission/oceania/tonga/|archive-date=13 June 2025|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The United Kingdom is accredited to Tonga through its [[British High Commission|high commission]] in [[Nuku'Alofa]].<ref>{{#invoke:cite|web|url=https://www.gov.uk/world/organisations/british-high-commission-nukualofa|title=British High Commission Nuku'Alofa|website=[[gov.uk|GOV.UK]]|access-date=24 October 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250516101625/https://www.gov.uk/world/organisations/british-high-commission-nukualofa|archive-date=16 May 2025|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe UK governed [[Kingdom of Tonga (1900–1970)|Tonga]] from 1900 until 1970, when Tonga achieved full independence.\n\nBoth countries share common membership of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]], the [[United Nations]], the [[World Health Organization]], and the [[World Trade Organization]]. Bilaterally the two countries have an Investment Agreement.<ref>{{#invoke:cite|web|title=Tonga - United Kingdom BIT (1997)|url=https://investmentpolicy.unctad.org/international-investment-agreements/treaties/bit/3031/tonga---united-kingdom-bit-1997-|website=[[UN Trade and Development]]|access-date=23 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501193755/https://investmentpolicy.unctad.org/international-investment-agreements/treaties/bit/3031/tonga---united-kingdom-bit-1997-|archive-date=1 May 2021|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United States}}||4 October 1972||See [[Tonga–United States relations]]\n\nThe United States and Tonga enjoy close cooperation on a range of international issues. Officers of the American Embassy in Suva, Fiji, are concurrently accredited to Tonga and make periodic visits since the United States has no permanent consular or diplomatic offices in Tonga. Although plans for a US consulate in Tonga were announced in 2008,<ref>[http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/news/stories/200805/s2247365.htm?tab=latest \"US to open consulate in Tonga\"], ABC Radio Australia, 16 May 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.radiofiji.com.fj/fullstory.php?id=17715 \"US consular office for Tonga\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717083853/http://www.radiofiji.com.fj/fullstory.php?id=17715 |date=17 July 2011 }}, Fiji Broadcasting Corporation, 9 February 2009.</ref> it has yet to be established.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/16092.htm \"U.S. Relations With Tonga\"], U.S. Department of State, 29 August 2014.</ref> In May 2023, the United&nbsp;States announced plans to establish an embassy in Tonga, as part of a larger regional push to strengthen ties with the Pacific.<ref name=\"embassy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/may/03/us-set-to-open-tonga-embassy-in-may-as-pacific-push-ramps-up |lang=en-GB |date=2023-05-02 |accessdate=2023-05-02 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=US set to open Tonga embassy in May as Pacific push ramps up}}</ref>\n\n[[Peace Corps]] Volunteers teach and provide technical assistance to Tongans. A large number of Tongans reside in the United States, particularly in [[Utah]], California and Hawaii.<ref name=\"US Department of State\">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/16092.htm |title=US Department of State |publisher=2009-2017.state.gov |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Tonga is accredited to the United States from its permanent mission to the United Nations in New York City and has a consulate-general in [[Burlingame, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tongaconsul.com/ |title=Home |publisher=Tongaconsul.com |date=1 May 2019 |access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n* United States has an embassy in [[Nuku’alofa]].\n|}\n\n==Commonwealth of Nations==\n\nTonga has been a member of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] since 4 June 1970.\n\nTonga was a British protected monarchy from 1900 to 1970, when it became an independent native monarchy within the Commonwealth of Nations, a status shared by [[Brunei]], [[Lesotho]], [[Malaysia]], and [[Eswatini]], which also have their own native monarchs.\n\n==Current foreign policy==\n\nTonga's foreign policy as of January 2009 has been described by [[Matangi Tonga]] as \"Look East\" – namely, as establishing closer diplomatic and economic relations with Asia (which actually lies to the north-west of the Pacific kingdom). Tonga retains cordial relations with the United States. Although it remains on good terms with the United Kingdom, the two countries do not maintain particularly close relations, and the United Kingdom closed its High Commission in Tonga in 2006. Tonga's relations with Oceania's regional powers, Australia and New Zealand, are very good.\n\n== International disputes ==\n\nIn 1972, Tonga laid claim to, and invaded, the tide-washed, isolated Minerva Reefs, some 480 kilometres southwest of Nuku'olofa, to thwart efforts by a private group, Ocean Life Research Foundation, to establish an independent [[Republic of Minerva]] (now the [[Principality of Minerva]]) on the reefs and surrounding quays. In November 2005, Fiji laid a complaint with the [[International Seabed Authority]] claiming ownership of the reefs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pidp.eastwestcenter.org/pireport/2005/November/11-01-15.htm |title=Fiji, Tonga dispute ownership of reef |publisher=Radio New Zealand International |date=1 November 2005 <!--accessdate unknown - did not work on 2007-12-21-->}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of diplomatic missions in Tonga]]\n*[[List of diplomatic missions of Tonga]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of the Commonwealth of Nations}}\n{{Foreign relations of Tonga}}\n{{Pacific Islands Forum}}\n{{Foreign relations of Oceania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Relations Of Tonga}}\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Tonga| ]]\n[[Category:Tonga and the Commonwealth of Nations]]"